## Learn: Rationalizing the Denominator

If a radical expression contains a radical in the denominator, you can rationalize the denominator by multiplying the numerator and denominator by a quantity that produces an exact root in the denominator.

### Watch Out

Do not stop until the result is in simplest form. Check that no radicals remain in the denominator and that individual radicals cannot be simplified further.

---

## Example 6 — Rationalize the Denominator

Simplify:

`cuberoot(250a^6) / cuberoot(7a)`

Use the Quotient Property of Radicals:

`= cuberoot(250a^6) / cuberoot(7a)`

Factor into cubes:

`= cuberoot(5^3 * 2 * (a^2)^3) / cuberoot(7a)`

`= 5a^2 cuberoot(2) / cuberoot(7a)`

Multiply numerator and denominator by `cuberoot(7^2 a^2)` to rationalize the denominator:

`= (5a^2 cuberoot(2) / cuberoot(7a)) * (cuberoot(7^2 a^2) / cuberoot(7^2 a^2))`

`= 5a^2 cuberoot(98a^2) / cuberoot(7^3 a^3)`

`= 5a^2 cuberoot(98a^2) / (7a)`

`= 5a cuberoot(98a^2) / 7`

---

## Example 7 — Use Conjugates to Rationalize the Denominator

Simplify:

`4x / (2sqrt(7) - 5)`

Multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate `2sqrt(7) + 5`:

`= (4x / (2sqrt(7) - 5)) * ((2sqrt(7) + 5) / (2sqrt(7) + 5))`

Multiply:

`= [4x(2sqrt(7)) + 4x(5)] / [(2sqrt(7))^2 + 5(2sqrt(7)) - 5(2sqrt(7)) - 5^2]`

`= (8xsqrt(7) + 20x) / (28 - 25)`

`= (8xsqrt(7) + 20x) / 3`

